info.title: compensation
info.description: The Compensation service enables applications to extend Workday's HCM Compensation features.

tags.name: scorecardResults
tags.description: Provides the ability to set up and retrieve Scores on Scorecard Results.

tags.name: scorecards
tags.description: Provides the ability to set up and retrieve Scores on Scorecard Results.

tags.name: timeAttestationPrompts
tags.description: Provides the ability to get the time attestation prompts that a worker would need to answer when checking in or out. Use all four fields of timeZone, worker, eventType, and dateTime to simulate the time clock event to retrieve the prompts that would be available on desktop. The prompts and their responses will be used to create worker time attestations. These worker time attestations would then be used when creating the actual time clock events.

tags.name: timeClockEvents
tags.description: These public APIs are designed to open up foundational Time Tracking functionality in REST. Use this API to give employees the ability to check in and check out of work and to review and modify their recent check-ins and check-outs. You can also use this API to enable managers to check in and check out of work for a worker, to view workers who are currently checked in for work, and to review and modify a worker's check-ins and check-outs.

tags.name: timeValidations
tags.description: Provides access to custom time entry validation information in Workday. These REST APIs enable employees to view validations related to the time they just entered, and managers to view validations related to the time they are reviewing.

tags.name: workerTimeAttestation
tags.description: Provides access to worker time attestation information in Workday. These REST APIs enable users to view worker time attestations related to the time entered and to create worker time attestations. There is no query. To view a worker time attestation provide the ID in the URL. IDs are returned in the workerTimeAttesatation field of GET /timeClockEvent and in the ID field of POST /workerTimeAttestation.

tags.name: workerTimeBlocks
tags.description: Provides access to worker time block information in Workday.

tags.name: Prompt Values
tags.description: Retrieves instances that can be used as values for other endpoint parameters in this service.

tags.name: jobPostings
tags.description: Provides the ability to retrieve job postings.

tags.name: prospects
tags.description: Provides the ability to retrieve and create prospect data.

tags.name: feedbackBadges
tags.description: Provides the ability to get available feedback badges for use in providing feedback.

tags.name: minimumWageRates
tags.description: Provides the ability to view federal, state, and local minimum wage rates.

tags.name: payGroupDetails
tags.description: Provides the ability to view pay group details. Inactive and External Pay Group Details are not supported.

tags.name: payGroups
tags.description: Provides the ability to view pay groups. Inactive and External Pay Groups are not supported.

tags.name: payrollInputs
tags.description: Provides the ability to get, add, update, and delete payroll inputs for workers and pay components. These REST APIs: * Are secured to the Worker Data: Payroll Public API (Payroll Input) and Self-Service: Payroll Public API (Payroll Input) security domains. * The POST, PATCH, DELETE methods for self-service users require Pay Component Security Segments. Self-service users can view their own Payroll Inputs using GET without a Pay Component Security Segment. * Pay Component Segment Security is only supported on the Self-Service: Payroll Public API (Payroll Input) security domain. The Segment-Based Security Group must use a Self-Service – Worker security group type as the basis. * Don't support Payroll Tax Location Mapping or Pay Components that require Special Entry.

tags.name: taxRates
tags.description: Use these REST APIs to access company SUI tax rates.

post.summary: Request a one-time payment for a worker with the specified ID.
post.description: Creates a one-time payment for a worker with the specified ID, and initiates the Request One-Time Payment business process. In the request body, specify at least these required fields: reason{id}, position{id}, oneTimePayments[ paymentCurrency{id}, oneTimePaymentPlan {id}]. Sample format for paymentAmount: "payment Amount": { "value": "2500" } Secured by: Request One-Time Payment (REST Service) Scope: Core Compensation

get.summary: Retrieves a collection of time entry validations.
get.description: Retrieves a collection of time entry validations for the specified worker on the specified date. This method requires the date and worker query parameters. The validation messages returned by this method indicate that the time entries failed the critical or warning custom validations configured in the Maintain Time Entry Validations task. Secured by: Process: Time Block REST APIs Scope: Time Tracking

parameters.description: The required date that determines the time entry validations. The method validates the time entries within week or time period of the specified date.

parameters.description: The maximum number of objects in a single response. The default is 20. The maximum is 100.

parameters.name: offset
parameters.description: The zero-based index of the first object in a response collection. The default is 0. Use offset with the limit parameter to control paging of a response collection. post.description: Creates a worker time block for the specified worker. Specify these required fields in the request body: * calendarDate and reportedQuantity - If the worker is hourly. * inTime, outTime, inTimeZone and outTimeZone - If the worker is in and out. * One of timeEntryCode, project, or projectPlanTask. These fields are mutually exclusive. Specify 1 of these fields in the request body. For the timeEntryCode id, you can use a returned id from GET /values/timeTypes/timeEntryCodes, which returns the time entry codes that the given worker is eligible for on the given date. For a valid project id, you can use a returned id from GET /values/timeTypes/projects, which you can filter by date and worker. For a valid projectPlanTask id, you can use a returned id from GET /values/timeTypes/projectPlanTasks, which you can filter by date, worker, and project. Secured by: Process: Time Block REST APIs Scope: Time Tracking

patch.summary: Updates a specified worker time block.
patch.description: Updates the worker time block for the specified worker with the specified data in the request body. The timeEntryCode, project, and projectPlanTask fields are mutually exclusive. You can only specify 1 of these fields in the request body. For the timeEntryCode id, you can use a returned id from GET /values/timeTypes/timeEntryCodes, which returns the time entry codes that the given worker is eligible for on the given date. For a valid project id, you can use a returned id from GET /values/timeTypes/projects, which you can filter by date and worker. For a valid projectPlanTask id, you can use a returned id from GET /values/timeTypes/projectPlanTasks, which you can filter by date, worker, and project. Secured by: Process: Time Block REST APIs Scope: Time Tracking

get.summary: Retrieves a summary of reported hours for a worker over a period.
get.description: Retrieves a summary of reported hours for a worker over a period. The period contains the specified date or, if not specified, it contains today's date. Secured by: Process: Time Block REST APIs, Process: Time Clock Event REST API's Scope: Time Tracking

parameters.name: ID
parameters.description: The Workday ID of the resource.

parameters.name: limit
parameters.description: The maximum number of objects in a single response. The default is 20. The maximum is 100.

parameters.name: offset
parameters.description: The zero-based index of the first object in a response collection. The default is 0. Use offset with the limit parameter to control paging of a response collection. Example: If limit is 5 and offset is 9, the response returns a collection of 5 objects starting with the 10th object.

parameters.name: periodDate
parameters.description: Contains the specified date used to match to a period containing the date. The default is today's date.

200.description: Successful response. A successful response can return no matched data.

submitText.description: Contains legal text the user must agree to in order to submit hours for review.

post.summary: Adds time review events for the specified worker.
post.description: Creates a time review event for the specified worker. This endpoint is typically used by managers or administrators to submit time on behalf of workers, or by workers themselves to submit their own time for approval. Specify these required fields in the request body: * date: the date that constructs the Time Review Event. The date is used to create Time Review Events for the Period or Week, depending on how that worker's Time Entry Template is configured. Additional optional field: * comment: comment related to the business process that persists on each Time Review Event. Comments are not allowed if disabled on the Enter Time business process. To get more information about Administrator-configured critical time validations, use the GET /timeValidations operation. This operation is equivalent to the Submit Time task in the Workday UI. The same validations and business rules apply. This includes any configured approvals, notifications, and audit trails. Sample Request: ``` { "date": "2024-01-26", "comment": "Submitting time for approval." } ``` Secured by: Manager: Time Tracking Manager Approval, Manager: Time Tracking Manager Edit and Approve, Submit Time (REST Service) Scope: Time Tracking, Time Tracking Hub

parameters.name: ID
parameters.description: The Workday ID of the resource.

date.description: The date used to create the time review event. The date uses the format: yyyy-mm-dd. If Submit by Time Period is enabled on the worker's Time Entry Template as of the provided date, time is submitted for the pay period. Otherwise, time is submitted for the week.

timeReviewEvents.description: Contains Time Review Events created in the Submit Time request.

position.description: Contains Position for Time Review Event if Independent Events for Multiple Jobs is enabled on the Time Entry Template.

descriptor.description: The display name of the instance

project.description: Contains \~Project\~ for Time Review Event if Independent Events for \~Project\~ is enabled on the Time Entry Template.

descriptor.description: The display name of the instance

status.description: Contains the current status of the business process.  For example: Successfully Completed, Denied, Terminated.

descriptor.description: The display name of the instance
The display name of the instance

comment.description: The comment that persists on each time review event. Comments are not allowed if comments are disabled for the Enter Time business process or for all business processes in the tenant. For more information, see Reference: Edit Tenant Setup - Business Processes in the Admin Guide.
comment.example: Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, cum choro singulis consectetuer ut, ubique iisque contentiones ex duo. Quo lorem etiam eu.

date.description: The date used to create the time review event. The date uses the format: yyyy-mm-dd. If Submit by Time Period is enabled on the worker's Time Entry Template as of the provided date, time is submitted for the pay period. Otherwise, time is submitted for the week.

get.summary: Retrieves a collection of time clock events for a worker for a date range.
get.description: Retrieves a collection of time clock events. You can filter by the time clock events by worker and date range. Secured by: Process: Time Clock Event REST API's Scope: Time Tracking

parameters.name: fromDate
parameters.description: The start date of the time event using the yyyy-mm-dd format.

parameters.name: limit
parameters.description: The maximum number of objects in a single response. The default is 20. The maximum is 100.

parameters.name: offset
parameters.description: The zero-based index of the first object in a response collection. The default is 0. Use offset with the limit parameter to control paging of a response collection. Example: If limit is 5 and offset is 9, the response returns a collection of 5 objects starting with the 10th object.

parameters.name: toDate
parameters.description: The end date of the time event using the yyyy-mm-dd format.

parameters.name: worker
parameters.description: The Workday ID of the worker for the time block or clock event. You can specify multiple worker query parameters.

200.description: Successful response. A successful response can return no matched data.

timeZone.description: The time zone of the event. To retrieve a list of valid time zone IDs, use the GET /values/timeValues/workerTimeZone operation.

put.summary: Updates the time clock event for the specified ID.
put.description: Updates the time clock event for the specified ID. Replaces the existing time clock event with the specified data in the request body. The timeEntryCode, project, and projectPlanTask fields are mutually exclusive. You can only specify 1 of these fields in the request body. For the timeEntryCode id, you can use a returned id from GET /values/timeTypes/timeEntryCodes, which returns the time entry codes that the given worker is eligible for on the given date. For a valid project id, you can use a returned id from GET /values/timeTypes/projects, which you can filter by date and worker. For a valid projectPlanTask id, you can use a returned id from GET /values/timeTypes/projectPlanTasks, which you can filter by date, worker, and project. Secured by: Process: Time Clock Event REST API's Scope: Time Tracking

get.description: Retrieves instances that can be used as values for other endpoint parameters in this service.

parameters.name: date
parameters.description: The effective date to look up time types for a given worker.

parameters.name: inOutCodeOnly
parameters.description: If true, returns only Time Entry Codes of the type In/Out. You must use these types with POST Time Clock Event.

parameters.name: limit
parameters.description: The maximum number of objects in a single response. The default and maximum is 1000.

parameters.name: offset
parameters.description: The zero-based index of the first object in a response collection. The default is 0. Use offset with the limit parameter to control paging of a response collection. Example: If limit is 5 and offset is 9, the response returns a collection of 5 objects starting with the 10th object.

parameters.name: project
parameters.description: The Workday ID of a project, used to filter the projectPlanTasks resource down to project plan tasks from a given project.

parameters.name: worker
parameters.description: The Workday ID of the worker to look up time types for.

 * FEEDBACK_COMPLETE - All interview feedback for this in-progress event was submitted, but the Interview event isn’t awaiting the Make Interview Decision step.
 * NOT_SCHEDULED - An interview hasn't been scheduled for an in-progress Interview event.
 * PENDING_FEEDBACK - An in-progress Interview event is waiting for interviewer feedback.
 * SCHEDULED - An interview is scheduled for an in-progress Interview event.
 * SUBMITTED_FEEDBACK - The logged-in user submitted feedback for an in-progress Interview event.
 * MAKE_INTERVIEW_DECISION - The make an interview decision step for the candidate."

patch.summary: Partially updates an existing payroll input instance.
patch.description: Partially updates an existing payroll input instance with the specified ID and the specified data in the request body. Before calling this PATCH method, call the GET /payrollInputs method to retrieve the current payroll input information. You cannot update the worker field with this PATCH method. The Pay Component Segment Security configuration is required. Note that Pay Component Segment Security is supported only on the Self-Service: Payroll Public API (Payroll Input) security domain. The Segment-Based Security Group must use a Self-Service – Worker security group type as the basis. **Starting in v2:** The fieldEditability field in the GET /payrollInputs/{ID} response determines the fields that you can update with the PATCH /payrollInputs method. Possible fieldEditability values: * all - All fields can be updated, except the worker field. * none - No fields can be updated. * endDateOnly - Only the endDate field can be updated. ** In v1: ** The lastPeriodCompleted and usedInCompletedResult fields in the GET /payrollInputs/{ID} response determine the fields you can update with this PATCH method: * If lastPeriodCompleted and usedInCompletedResult are both false, all fields can be updated, except the worker field. * If lastPeriodCompleted and usedInCompletedResult are both true, no fields can be updated. * If only usedInCompletedResult is true, only the endDate field can be updated. Secured by: Self-Service: Payroll Public API (Payroll Input), Worker Data: Payroll Public API (Payroll Input) Scope: Core Payroll

Self-service users can view all of their own Payroll Inputs. **Starting in v2:** The fieldEditability field in the GET /payrollInputs/{ID} response determines the fields that you can update with the PATCH /payrollInputs method. Possible fieldEditability values: * all - All fields can be updated, except the worker field. * none - No fields can be updated. * endDateOnly - Only the endDate field can be updated. ** In v1: ** The lastPeriodCompleted and usedInCompletedResult fields in the GET /payrollInputs/{ID} response determine the fields that you can update with the PATCH /payrollInputs method. * If lastPeriodCompleted and usedInCompletedResult are both false, all fields can be updated, except the worker field. * If lastPeriodCompleted and usedInCompletedResult are both true, no fields can be updated. * If only usedInCompletedResult is true, only the endDate field can be updated. Secured by: Self-Service: Payroll Public API (Payroll Input), Worker Data: Payroll Public API (Payroll Input) Scope: Core Payroll

post.summary: Creates a single or a collection of Company SUI Rates.
post.description: Creates a single or a collection of company SUI rates. To create a single company SUI rate, specify the single JSON object in the request body. To create multiple company SUI rates, specify "bulk=true" as a query parameter. You must specify the JSON object collection in data[ ] in the request body. The maximum collection size is 100. In the request body, specify at least these required fields: companyInstance, stateInstance, taxCode, startDate. Secured by: Process: Tax Filing/W-2s (Run) - USA Scope: USA Payroll

--- | ---

A12 | Enter an Applicable Rate that's less than 10, contains up to 6 decimal places, and is a positive number. Example: 9.999999. Request Element Values - Company: [company] ([companyWID]), State: [state] ([stateWID]), Start Date: ([start])
A12 | Enter an Employer Identification Number that's valid, and isn't null or 'null'. Request Element Values - Company: [company] ([companyWID]), State: [state] ([stateWID]), Start Date: ([start])
A12 | You must enter exactly 'W_SUIER' as the taxCode. Request Element Values - Company: [company] ([companyWID]), State: [state] ([stateWID]), Start Date: ([start])
A119 | Enter an End Date that's after or on the Start Date. Request Element Values - Company: [company] ([companyWID]), State: [state] ([stateWID]), Start Date: ([start])
A121 | Enter an End Date that's not between the start and end dates of another row. Request Element Values - Company: [company] ([companyWID]), State: [state] ([stateWID]), Start Date: ([start])
A124 | Enter a Start Date that's not between the start and end dates of an existing row. Request Element Values - Company: [company] ([companyWID]), State: [state] ([stateWID]), Start Date: ([start])

interviewStatuses.description:
"All applicable interview statuses for an Interview event. Statuses can be: 
 * AWAITING_ME - An in-progress Interview event is waiting for the logged-in user's feedback. 
 * COMPLETED - An Interview event is complete.
 * FEEDBACK_COMPLETE - All interview feedback for this in-progress event was submitted, but the Interview event isn’t awaiting the Make Interview Decision step.
 * NOT_SCHEDULED - An interview hasn't been scheduled for an in-progress Interview event.
 * PENDING_FEEDBACK - An in-progress Interview event is waiting for interviewer feedback.
 * SCHEDULED - An interview is scheduled for an in-progress Interview event.
 * SUBMITTED_FEEDBACK - The logged-in user submitted feedback for an in-progress Interview event.
 * MAKE_INTERVIEW_DECISION - The make an interview decision step for the candidate."
